            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">A collection of fourteen prayers, one for each night and
                     day of the week. For a detailed structure and analysis of the prayers, see
                     Pablo Beneito and Stephen Hirtenstein Seven Days of the Heart (Oxford, 2000),
                     with critical edition as Prayers for the Week (Oxford, 2021).</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">There are no historic mss. and all the surviving texts are
                  late, though always attributed to IA. The earliest dated copy is Carullah 1094
                  (939H), but Veliyuddin 1833 may be older. According to Stephen Hirtenstein and
                  Pablo Beneito it is authentic on textual grounds, and the lack of early copies is
                  attributed to the work being only copied for close disciples, not open diffusion.
                  There is another relatively early manuscript of Evradü’l-Eyyami’s-Seb’a (dated
                  949H or 950H) in Topkapi E.H. 1072 with 42 folios according to the online
                  catalogue at https://topkapisarayi.gov.tr/en/manuscripts</note>
